	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64376332"><p><div class="quote"><p>If you run into hardware problems on OpenBSD, you can run the OS inside a VM for a small performance hit.</p></div><p>The only significant appeal of OpenBSD is security, and that appeal is lost when not running it on the bare metal. There is literally no reason to run it in a VM. By the time I'm resorting to a VM, I am already gaining separation, and I might as well just put Linux in the VM too.</p><p>The biggest problem (IME) with OpenBSD is hardware support, and this is caused by developers not giving a shit about users' problems; When you report a problem the obsd devs just want to know when you're providing a patch. The answe<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64376332">

